{
  "doc_id": "29004",
  "text": "The pathogenic basis of particular in-frame dystrophin deletions reflects the number of exons lost, where deletions of 34 or more exons are usually associated with severe pathology [CITATION_1] , or secondary effects on pre-mRNA processing. Other in-frame deletions may have severe consequences, due to the loss of a crucial functional domain within dystrophin, eg the actin or beta-dystroglycan binding regions. Mutations in the 5' region of the DMD gene frequently manifest as exceptions to the reading frame rule [CITATION_2] , and various mechanisms have been proposed to impact on the consequences of these mutations, including re-initiation of translation [CITATION_3] and splicing perturbations [CITATION_4] .",
